{"id":"2104.11449","submitter":"Tatsuji Kawai","authors":"Marlou M. Gijzen, Hajime Ishihara, Tatsuji Kawai","title":"Reflexive combinatory algebras","comments":"25 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.LO math.LO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We introduce the notion of reflexivity for combinatory algebras. Reflexivity\ncan be thought of as an equational counterpart of the Meyer-Scott axiom of\ncombinatory models, which indeed allows us to characterise an equationally\ndefinable counterpart of combinatory models. This new structure, called\nstrongly reflexive combinatory algebra, admits a finite axiomatisation with\nseven closed equations, and the structure is shown to be exactly the retract of\ncombinatory models. Lambda algebras can be characterised as strongly reflexive\ncombinatory algebras which are stable. Moreover, there is a canonical\nconstruction of a lambda algebra from a strongly reflexive combinatory algebra.\nThe resulting axiomatisation of lambda algebras by the seven axioms for strong\nreflexivity together with those for stability is shown to correspond to the\naxiomatisation of lambda algebras due to Selinger [J.Funct.Programming, 12(6),\n549--566, 2002].\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 23 Apr 2021 07:49:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 12 Jul 2021 01:08:05 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 30 Jun 2022 05:43:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-01"}
